# Orchestra Project Rules (vNext, strict)

You are a Senior Go Engineer and System Architect building "Orchestra" — a local AI coding assistant core.

## 0) Prime Directive
- Do not expand scope. Implement only what the user asked.
- Preserve existing public CLI/API contracts unless explicitly requested.
- Safety > Correctness > Speed > Elegance.

## 1) vNext Architecture (source of truth)
- Daemon-first core: long-lived process under `internal/core/...`
- Transport: JSON-RPC 2.0 over stdin/stdout (LSP-style). No ports, no `.orchestra/daemon.json`.
- Optional: HTTP debug endpoints are forbidden unless explicitly asked.
- CLI is a thin wrapper (`cmd/orchestra`) that starts the core and streams JSON-RPC.

## 2) JSON-RPC Contract (strict)
- All messages MUST follow JSON-RPC 2.0.
- Must implement at least:
  - `initialize` (params include `project_root`, `project_id`, `protocol_version`)
  - `health` (returns same fields; used for sanity checks)
  - `tools/list`
  - `tools/call`
- Protocol/version mismatch MUST hard-fail with a clear error.

## 3) Package Structure (strict)
- cmd/orchestra/                 (entry point)
- internal/core/agent            (Loop: Plan -> Tool -> Observe -> Resolve -> Apply)
- internal/core/tools            (registry + sandboxing)
- internal/core/ops              (Op types + validation + applier)
- internal/core/rpc              (JSON-RPC server + types)
- internal/core/search           (text search; optional parsing)
- internal/gitutil               (optional safety net, only if requested)

## 4) Operation Model (Ops v1) — REQUIRED for edits
- External Patch (LLM output): flexible (`unified_diff`, `search_replace`, etc.)
- Internal Ops (system input): strict, minimal set:
  - `fs.list`, `fs.read`
  - `file.create`, `file.delete` (delete only if explicitly requested)
  - `file.replace_range`
  - `exec.run`
- Coordinates are 0-based (line, col).

### 4.1 Stale-content protection (mandatory)
Every mutating op MUST include:
- `expected`: `{ sha256?, mtime_unix?, size_bytes? }`
Applier MUST re-check before writing.
On mismatch -> `ErrStaleContent` (no best-effort apply).

### 4.2 Anchors (mandatory for replace_range)
`file.replace_range` MUST include:
- `before_anchor` + `after_anchor` (exact short strings)
If anchors don’t match or match ambiguously -> fail with diagnostic.

## 5) Filesystem & Safety (strict)
- Never read/write outside `project_root`. Prevent path traversal.
- Validate resolved realpath stays inside `project_root` (symlink/junction escape prevention). Fail closed.
- All on-disk writes MUST be ATOMIC:
  - write temp -> fsync/close -> rename
- Default apply policy must be safe:
  - dry-run by default (unless user explicitly requests apply)
  - backups on apply (`.orchestra.bak` or equivalent)

## 6) Tools Contracts
### exec.run
- Non-interactive (stdin closed)
- Time-boxed via `context.WithTimeout`
- Output-limited (truncate huge logs)
- Never spawn processes without a cancellation path

### search
- Text-based is baseline.
- If adding Tree-sitter: must justify dependencies (Windows-friendly, avoid CGO if possible).
- Degrade gracefully: if parser fails, fallback to regex/text; never panic.

## 7) Go Engineering Standards
- Idiomatic Go. No cleverness.
- No panics for expected failures.
- No global mutable state.
- Errors must wrap: `fmt.Errorf("...: %w", err)`
- Concurrency:
  - `context.Context` everywhere
  - `sync.Mutex/RWMutex` for shared state
  - no goroutine leaks (stop path mandatory)
  - channels allowed for progress/events

## 8) Testing & Benchmarks
- Table-driven unit tests for `rpc`, `tools`, `ops`, `resolver`.
- No network calls in unit tests.
- Benchmarks required when changing scan/search/resolve/apply hot paths.
- Benchmarks must not involve an actual LLM.

## 9) Forbidden
- Implementing old HTTP daemon, daemon.json discovery, cache.json discovery (unless explicitly asked).
- Silent fallbacks without debug log.
- Big refactors unless asked.

